  "voiceover": "How soon did people start saying Jesus rose from the dead? The skeptic's best move is to call it a legend — a story that grew over decades, blurred by time until a dying-and-rising god emerged. But there's a problem. Writing around AD 55, the apostle Paul stops and recites a creed he says he did not invent — one he 'received' and 'delivered.' It's 1 Corinthians 15: that Christ died for our sins, was buried, was raised on the third day, and appeared. And the creed carries its own age. It uses the rabbinic language of received-and-delivered tradition, its wording isn't Paul's usual Greek, and it names Peter by his Aramaic name, Cephas — the marks of a formula older than the letter that quotes it. So count backward. The crucifixion is around AD 30. Paul says that within a few years of his conversion he went to Jerusalem and met Peter and James — the very men the creed names as witnesses. That puts the creed within about two to five years of the cross. This isn't a Christian-only conclusion. The atheist New Testament scholar Gerd Lüdemann dated the tradition to the first two years after the crucifixion. Now, stated honestly: this does not by itself prove the resurrection. What it proves is that the belief was early, sincere, and anchored in named eyewitnesses — far too early for legend to have done its slow work. Not a legend that grew. A claim from the very start.",
